# Crime Section Classification System

An NLP-based multi-class text classification system that maps free-text crime descriptions to their corresponding **IPC (Indian Penal Code)** legal sections — built to support faster, more consistent classification for legal-tech and law enforcement use cases.

## Overview

Crime descriptions are typically recorded as free, unstructured text. Mapping a description to the correct IPC section is normally done manually, based on the reporting officer's or legal staff's familiarity with the law — a process that can be slow and inconsistent across different reviewers.

This project automates that first-pass classification: given a crime description, the model predicts the most likely IPC section(s) it falls under, acting as a decision-support tool rather than a final legal authority.

## Features

- End-to-end NLP pipeline: tokenization, stopword removal, stemming, and TF-IDF vectorization
- Multi-class classification across multiple IPC sections
- Benchmarking of three classifiers — Naive Bayes, SVM, and Logistic Regression — with the best-performing model selected via F1-score and confusion matrix analysis
- Iterative feature engineering and hyperparameter tuning to improve classification performance
- ~75–80% prediction accuracy on the held-out test set *(see [Notes on reported metrics](#notes-on-reported-metrics))*

## Tech Stack

| Category | Tools |
|---|---|
| Language | Python |
| NLP | NLTK |
| ML / Vectorization | Scikit-learn, TF-IDF |
| Models | Naive Bayes, SVM, Logistic Regression |

## Pipeline

```
Raw crime description
        │
        ▼
Text Preprocessing  (lowercasing → tokenization → stopword removal → stemming)
        │
        ▼
TF-IDF Vectorization  (free text → numeric feature vectors)
        │
        ▼
Classifier  (Naive Bayes / SVM / Logistic Regression)
        │
        ▼
Predicted IPC Section
```

