## Usage

### Training

```bash
python src/train.py --data data/crime_descriptions.csv
```

### Predicting on new text

```python
from src.predict import predict_section

description = "The accused forcibly entered the premises and stole valuables."
predicted_section = predict_section(description)
print(predicted_section)
```
> Adjust function/file names above to match your actual code interface.

## Methodology

**Preprocessing** — Each crime description is lowercased, tokenized, stripped of stopwords, and stemmed to consolidate grammatical variants of the same term (e.g., *"stole"*, *"stealing"*, *"stolen"*) into a shared root, strengthening the relevant signal for classification.

**Feature extraction** — TF-IDF (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency) converts each preprocessed description into a numeric vector, weighting words by how frequent they are within a given description versus how rare/distinctive they are across the dataset as a whole. This helps the model focus on legally distinctive terms rather than generic, frequently occurring words.

**Modeling** — Three classifiers were trained and benchmarked under the same preprocessing and feature extraction pipeline: Multinomial Naive Bayes, Linear SVM, and Logistic Regression. Models were compared using F1-score (not just raw accuracy, due to class imbalance across IPC sections) and confusion matrix analysis to identify which sections were most often confused with one another.

**Tuning** — Performance was improved through iterative feature engineering (e.g., adjusting TF-IDF vocabulary size and n-gram range) and hyperparameter tuning (e.g., the regularization parameter for SVM/Logistic Regression, smoothing parameter for Naive Bayes), typically via grid search with cross-validation.

