## Limitations

- Classifies based on textual patterns rather than legal reasoning — cannot account for intent, context, or nuance the way a legal professional can
- Performance likely varies across classes; IPC sections with fewer training examples are predicted less reliably than well-represented ones
- A single crime can genuinely fall under multiple IPC sections, but this system performs single-label classification (one predicted section per description) rather than multi-label

## Future Improvements

- Extend to multi-label classification to reflect that a single crime can fall under multiple IPC sections
- Address class imbalance more rigorously (class weighting, targeted data collection for underrepresented sections)
- Explore embedding-based or transformer-based text representations as an alternative/complement to TF-IDF
- Validate performance with a properly logged baseline-vs-tuned comparison rather than ad hoc estimates

## Notes on Reported Metrics

The accuracy and improvement figures referenced in this README reflect approximate results observed during development. If you are republishing or citing this project, it's worth re-running evaluation on your final model and dataset split to confirm and report exact, reproducible numbers.

## Disclaimer

This project is intended as a decision-support and educational tool, not a substitute for professional legal judgment. Predicted IPC sections should be reviewed and confirmed by a qualified person before any real-world legal or law-enforcement use.

